			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">What is cool:
<br />

<br />
1) Exp debt instead Exp loss at death. Also the shard recovery instead of corpse recovery and the ability to "sleep off" debt by staying logged off for several hours. Some people will play with 60% or more debt around their neck. I can't hack more than about 15% with out feeling Iike I should quit.
<br />

<br />
2) You never lose your equipment, your equipment is your stats, so you have to have it always.
<br />

<br />
3) Large number of worthwhile quests. Although many quests end giving to something you can't use, they are good for a little bit of money and some experience. There are many routine quests that everyone ends up doing such as the so called 'Armor Quest' series.
<br />

<br />
4) Spell and Skill upgrades, there are many levels of upgrades. It feels like you really get something when a spell or skill is upgraded 2 or 3 levels from the default.
<br />

<br />
What sucks:
<br />

<br />
1) Shared group debt is number one on the sucks list. There appears to be a "bonus" of extra debt for dying in a group, so if the group wipes, the debt bar gets an extra spike. If some idiot falls off a Griffon tower on his way to join a group, everyone in the group gets to share a piece of his debt. Players don't have much trust in other players, many avoid joining a group unless they know some of the people. A mistake or two by one player can often cause players to bail out of the group. A group wipe is almost always a group-ender. There are a multitude of problems with the shared debt system, as it stands now, it sucks, but it can be fixed.
<br />

<br />
2) Bad Lag, and SOE's lack of response to it when it begins to show it's ugly head. SOE addresses lag problems by instancing zones when they become too crowded. The problem is that they don't seem to have figured out that all zones can get over-crowded. So everyone complains as the pack move into high end zones, then after a week of lag problems in the higher end zone, SOE gets around to instancing them. Bah!
<br />

<br />
3) Lack of Solo/Duo content. There are solo mobs here and there. For some reason SOE decided to put hardly any in and mix them up with group mobs. The solo content that is there is pretty uninteresting. It would be nice to see some instanced solo/duo zones.
<br />

<br />
4) Unbalanced crafting system. Depending on what tradeskill road you take, you might have an easy time of leveling or a really slow time of leveling. Some tradskillers will find tons of the resources they need, while others will find it much harder to get what they need. Some tradeskill classes have simple combines for good experience and profit to an NPC vendor, while others are forced into relying on other players for materials and quite a bit of low level crafting work just to get raw materials for higher end work. Some crafting professions are totally devoid of recipies, SOE definately released the game with a broken crafting system for some professions, it's a mess.
<br />

<br />

<br />
And now for a gut-busting-bonus of SOE Fucked Up Big Time:
<br />

<br />
Selling to NPC vendors has been shut off. Yep, SOE decided to deal with crafting macro exploiters by shutting off all selling to NPC vendors until they can adjust the selling price downwards on everything. 
<br />

<br />
The patch last night shut off selling crafting items to NPC's and appears to have even affected selling common mob drops. Only chest loot can be sold, from reports by some players this morning. This has caused a huge outcry on the EQ II forum and SOE is in full damage control mode (sure to be a Page 80 before the day is done): <a href="http://eqiiforums.station.sony.com/eq2/board/message?board.id=general_tradeskill&message.id=15464" target="_blank" class="postlink">http://eqiiforums.station.sony.com/eq2/board/message?board.id=general_tradeskill&message.id=15464</a>
<br />

<br />
The official line is that players were not selling to players because there was no incentive to bother selling to players if the NPC would buy the item. In reality some players have found ways to macro there way to high amounts of money. I talked to one guy that had 3 Platinum already, and that is just a huge amount in EQ II. There doesn't seem to be a logical way he could have made the money with out macroing something.
<br />

<br />
People are threatening to quit or stating that they have already decided to quit over just this, although some say it was just the last straw. Most peiople support the idea of stopping macro exploiting, but think that the way SOE is doing this is a rip-off to average players. All I know is another friend just bailed out for WoW over this.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
