			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Actually, Tinc, EQ2 and WoW are both more complex than EQ.  If anything you would be far more accurate saying EQ = EQ2 or WoW for dummies.  ;)
<br />

<br />
I tend to agree with Flunkie's plusses, but disagree with most of his minuses:
<br />

<br />
Shared xp debt is a very good thing.  It means that it's not only the tank that ends up with xp debt with the cleric fails to heal them or the group in general fails to support them.  If you don't like debt then don't be in a group that sucks - simple as that.  I think the shared debt idea is far better than any other alternatives.
<br />

<br />
Instanced zones are *automatic*, not manual.  Every zone aside from cities are instanced in EQ2 and they fire off a second or third instance when the load gets high.  There's nothing about "SOE getting around to instancing" - they are already instanced.  I've yet to find real lag in any zone I've been in that hasn't been caused by client side problems (ie underpowered vid card) not server.
<br />

<br />
The solo/duo content is sparse but EQ2 (just like EQ1) was designed as a social game.  I don't think that providing for groups over solo players is a bad thing at all.  If I wanted a single player game then I'd go play Diablo or Half Life.  I've not really had a problem finding solo mobs though in any case, at least in the outdoor zones (Commonlands, Nek Forest, Enchanted Lands).
<br />

<br />
I don't think the tradeskill system is a mess at all.  If anything, the only class that is vaguely "broken" was Provisioner - which has zero dependancies on other classes, easy combines and decent profit to merchants.  The system was designed to be interdependant and the trick to getting good results is to be social - find someone to harvest resources for you; find someone else to make subcombines; provide subcombines to others, etc.  Again, EQ isn't a solo game and aspiring to solo domination is just futile.
<br />

<br />
As a provisioner, I can see why they shut off the merchant buying.  It really was insane profitmaking - especially once you got to Tier 3 and above stuff.  I didn't need to macro anything to be making almost 1gp profit per stack of combines (which took around 15 minutes) and with hitting 30 last night, I would be getting closer to 4gp profit per stack.  That was *definitely* broken, not to mention chocolate cakes which were a Lv28 recipe that you could get ingredients entirely from the wholesaler merchant for around 50cp and sold back for 4sp...
<br />

<br />
So, while shutting down vendors for the near term definitely sucks for my crafting and the economy in general, I really don't think it's going to be a permanent solution.  They're just doing a pass through to fix the major discrepancies in price than existed.
<br />

<br />
Trust me - 4pp is definitely in the realms of possibility without macroing, especially for jewelers, provisioners and carpenters who got the early start on everyone else.
<br />

<br />
Overall though, EQ2 is still definitely a better game than EQ1.  More complexity, more interdependancy and a far richer world.  I think WoW is in the same league.
<br />

<br />
Dd</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
