			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; I noticed a huge decrease in the number of player on my server last night. I don't know if people let their account lapse over the 30 days or many quit over the merchant fiasco or a combination of both. But zones that used to have 2 instances with 100+ in each two days ago had 80 in one and 40 in the other last night.&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;
<br />

<br />
I think casual players who are more concerned about PVE than PVP (or PVP comparisons) are discovering that despite all the "WoW and EQ2 are WAY better than EQ1" talk they still find EQ1 delivers the most enjoyment.  There are a lot of reasons why someone would still think EQ1 is a "better" game than 2 or WoW despite the googly-eyed posts you are seeing in the opening month for these games.  Bottome line, games appeal to people for a wide variety of reasons. Saying that EQ2 is "better" than WoW or EQ1 is nonsense.  Ditto for those that would say either these games is "better" than EQ2.  For me,  it is probably not possible for EQ2 or WOW to be as "good" as EQ1. That is a function of my play style (Casual-PVE player), the bonds I have built with people in EQ1 and the large amount fo content still to be experienced in EQ1. 
<br />

<br />
It also seems that the "EQ2 is so much better than EQ1" posts have taken on almost a desperate tone.   I remember this same phenomenon with DoAC and I always thought the people posting about that sounded ridiculous.  Asserting  subjective opinions as fact (EQ2 is <span style="font-weight: bold">better </span> than EQ1 or vice versa) always makes me wonder whom the speaker is trying to convince.  Maybe if you say it enough times you will convince yourself as well!
<br />

<br />

<br />
Akhbar</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
